let me rearrange [existing code](https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/nautilus/blob/master/src/nautilus-directory.c#L495) a few
```cpp
NautilusDirectory *
nautilus_directory_get_internal (GFile *location, gboolean create) {
    NautilusDirectory *directory;

    /* Create the hash table first time through. */
    ensure_directories_table_present ();

    /* If the object is already in the hash table, look it up. */
    directory = g_hash_table_lookup (directories,location);
    if (directory)
    {
        return nautilus_directory_ref (directory); // -->MARK-C
    }

    if (!create)
    {
        return NULL;
    }

    /* Create a new directory object instead. */
    // -->MARK-A
    directory = nautilus_directory_new (location);
    if (directory == NULL)
    {
        return NULL;
    }
    /* Put it in the hash table. */
    g_hash_table_insert (directories,
                         directory->details->location,
                         directory);
    // -->MARK-B
    return directory;
}
```

the code from `MARK-A` to `MARK-B` is an equivalent of
```cpp
directory = g_hash_table_lookup (directories,location);
```
for the case when the directory is already here, but please note, that in first case we are returning it extra referenced (`MARK-C`) but for [`MARK-A`..`MARK-B`] we return it as is.

There is possible use case, when it becomes a bug:

In order to use all the power of `nautilus-directory-async.c` we are going to implement the following inheritance (pseudo code):

```java
class CustomDirectory extends NautilusVFSDirectory implements NautilusDirectoryProvider {
    // some methods are extended, like this, but most of them
    // simply re-use parent's functionality
    void onFilesAdded(GList file_list)
    {
       // do some tweaks on the files like populating extended properties and such
       ...
       // then chain up to parent
       super (file_list);
    }
}
```

and to get it working seamless with `nautilus-directory-async` we define our `NautilusFile` derivative:
```java
class CustomFile extends NautilusVFSFile implements GFileIface {
   // we need to be a GFile to get async directory properly working

}
```

It is clear that we expect to receive our own files, not a raw `NautilusVFSFile`s ones inside `onFilesAdded`. But if we look into the code of [`nautilus-directory-async.c`](https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/nautilus/blob/master/src/nautilus-directory-async.c#L956) then we can see:
```cpp
        {
            /* new file, create a nautilus file object and add it to the list */
            file = nautilus_file_new_from_info (directory, file_info);
            nautilus_directory_add_file (directory, file);
            file->details->is_added = TRUE;
            added_files = g_list_prepend (added_files, file);
        }

```
(that is okay), but inside [`nautilus_file_new_from_info`](https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/nautilus/blob/master/src/nautilus-file.c#L718) we can see:
```cpp
nautilus_file_new_from_info (NautilusDirectory *directory,
                             GFileInfo         *info)
{
    ...
    file = NAUTILUS_FILE (g_object_new (NAUTILUS_TYPE_VFS_FILE, NULL));
    nautilus_file_set_directory (file, directory);
    ...
}
```
which looks at least strange, because the directory provides the dedicated method for doing this kind of job [`new_file_from_filename`](https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/nautilus/blob/master/src/nautilus-directory.h#L146):
```cpp
        /* Subclasses can use this to create custom files when asked by the user
         * or the nautilus cache. */
        NautilusFile * (* new_file_from_filename) (NautilusDirectory *directory,
                                                   const char        *filename,
                                                   gboolean           self_owned);

```

IMHO, the code for new file should be [like this](https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/nautilus/blob/master/src/nautilus-directory.h#L252):
```cpp
nautilus_file_new_from_info (NautilusDirectory *directory,
                             GFileInfo         *info)
{
    ...
    gchar *filename = g_file_info_get_name(info);
    file = nautilus_directory_new_file_from_filename (directory, filename, FALSE);
    ...
}

```
which would create proper files regardless of actual directory...

Does it make any sense?

Thanks

